`rackabel explain <code>` prints cargo-style long-form help for an error code: what
happened, why, and the concrete next step. Codes are case-insensitive.

```
$ rackabel explain RK0001
RK0001 — No rackabel.toml found

rackabel looks for a rackabel.toml in the current directory and its
parents. None was found. Run `rackabel new` to scaffold a project, or
cd into an existing project directory.

Every rackabel command (build, deploy, pack, validate) runs against a
project rooted at a rackabel.toml. It is the single source of truth for
the extension's name, version, entry point, and toolchain.

To fix:
- `cd` into the project folder (the one holding rackabel.toml), or
- run `rackabel new <name>` to scaffold a new project here.

```

A lower-case code resolves the same explanation.

```
$ rackabel explain rk0303
RK0303 — No Ableton Live install found

No Ableton Live install was found (or all installs are below 12.4.5).
Install Live Suite 12.4.5+ and enable the Extensions beta, then rerun
`rackabel doctor`.

Live Extensions require Live Suite 12.4.5 or newer with the Extensions
beta enabled. rackabel scans /Applications for `Ableton Live*.app`; you
can also point it at a specific app with `--live <path>` or the
ABLETON_APP environment variable.

To fix:
1. Install Ableton Live Suite 12.4.5 or newer.
2. Enable the Extensions beta (Live → Settings → … → Beta).
3. Run `rackabel doctor` to confirm it is detected.

```

A validation code explains the matching `rackabel validate` rule.

```
$ rackabel explain RK4003
RK4003 — Version not bumped vs the last packed version

The current version is not newer than the last version you packed.

rackabel records the last packed version in .rackabel/state.toml. If you
pack again with the same (or an older) version, existing users would not
receive the update, and two different builds would share one version
number — a support nightmare.

To fix:
- bump [extension].version (e.g. 1.2.0 → 1.2.1 for a fix, → 1.3.0 for
a feature), then rerun. `rackabel validate` reports the last packed
version it is comparing against.

```

An unknown code is a usage error (exit 2) and lists every valid code, so it is never
a dead end.

```
$ rackabel explain RK9999
? 2
error: no such error code `RK9999` [RK0001]
  help: valid codes: RK0001, RK0002, RK0003, RK0101, RK0102, RK0103, RK0401, RK0402, RK0403, RK0404, RK0201, RK0202, RK0301, RK0302, RK0303, RK0304, RK0305, RK0306, RK0307, RK0308, RK0309, RK0310, RK0311, RK0312, RK1301, RK1302, RK1303, RK1304, RK1305, RK1306, RK1307, RK1308, RK4001, RK4002, RK4003, RK4004, RK4005, RK4006, RK4007, RK4008, RK1309, RK1310, RK1311, RK0405, RK0104
(run `rackabel explain RK0001` for details)

```
